result.execSummary:
The defendant Ashanti Malachi Coates was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Resisting or Obstructing an Officer, a class A misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 946.41(1).
  • Disorderly Conduct, a class B misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 947.01(1).

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

Defendant Ashanti Malachi Coates in court with attorney Francisco Araiza.  Defendant Ashanti Malachi Coates in custody.  Alex T. Mueller appeared for the State of Wisconsin.  Deputy court clerk cmt.
Sentencing proceeded.  Statements by parties.  

As to Count 1:  Defendant ordered to serve 9 months in the House of Correction credit of 180 days time served.  Court STAYED the sentence and placed the defendant on probation with the Mental Health Unit for 24 months.

As to Count 2:  Court sentences defendant to serve 90 days  in the House of Correction with credit for 90 days, a TIME SERVED DISPOSITION.  Due to indegency, Court waives all costs, fees and surcharges due to indegency.  

Conditions of Probation:  
*Stay on all prescribed medications. 
*Alcohol and drug assessment and comply with any treatment deemed necessary by the department.
*Maintain absolute sobriety.  No illegal drugs.
*No contact with BP gas station at 4715 S 27th St, Mobil gas station at 605 South 1st St, Sadhana S., and Alison C.
*Court waives all costs, fees and surcharges due to indegency.

Hearing proceeded.  Negotiations set forth by the state.

As to Counts 1 and 2:  Defendant changes his plea to GUILTY.  Defendant examined as to his plea, advised of his Constitutional rights and the maximum penalty.   Defendant advised that if not a United States Citizen, deportation is possible.  Court found that defendant knowingly, voluntarily and intelligently waived his rights.  Guilty Plea Questionnaire/Waiver of Rights and Addendum received and filed.  Parties stipulate to the complaint as a factual basis to sustain defendant's plea.  Court found defendant guilty and ordered a Judgment of Conviction be entered on the record.  Arguments heard as to bail.

Competency Hearing proceeded.  State does not challenge Dr. Pankiewicz's report.  Defense does challenge Dr. Pankiewicz's report.  Court qualified Dr. Pankiewicz to testify as an expert.  Sworn for the State:  Dr. Pankiewicz.  Testimony closed.  Arguments heard.
After review of all evidence, report, and testimony of Dr. Pankiewicz, Court finds defendant incompetent to proceed at this time but is likely to become competent.  Court ordered defendant commitment for treatment for incompetency.  Order signed and filed.  The sheriff shall arrange for transportation of the defendant to the treatment facility.
